Repetition control structure (loops) warmup\
1. write a sub to compute factorial(n)\
2. test it with inbuilt vba function fact\
3. modify your sub to be a function called myfactorial(n)\
4. use myfactorial(n) to compute exp(x) via a series expansion 1 + x + (x^2)/(2!) + (x^3)/(3!) + ... (x^N)/(N!) where N the number of terms is determined by the user. \
\
Notes : \
1. Part A task 4 involves looping n from 1 to N and for each term making a function call to myfactorial(n)\
2. Accuracy of approximation to be checked by ensuring the absolute difference between actual and expected is less than some threshold. This threshold may be an additional input from the user or you can hard code it.\
3. you will get memory stack overflow if you use integers or single precision numbers. For scientific tasks it is usually safer to use the data type double.\
